This paper deals with privacy-preserving protocols for sensitive data, which is a topic that falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR). The paper introduces new information-theoretic metrics for utility and privacy, which suggests that it may also fall under the category of information theory (cs.IT). The paper also discusses the tradeoff between privacy and utility, which is a common theme in machine learning (cs.LG) and data management (cs.DB). Finally, the paper presents quantitative analysis of popular protocols, which suggests that it may also fall under the category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS).
